The motivation for the present analysis was to flesh out certain inadequacies of the TEI approach to stand-off annotation, in order to see how many of the problems have causes internal to the TEI Guidelines, and how many can be attributed to external factors, such as the lack of sufficiently developed generic XML tools or the inadequacies of standards assumed by the TEI. The ultimate question, therefore, is: should the TEI be used for modern stand-off text encoding at all, or should developers turn to other formats, such as the excellent PAULA toolkit (cf.
), the slightly aged XCES (
) or the more generic but still incomplete LAF family of standards (
).

